{"key":"post-16384134","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16384134</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;YouNeedMT said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Doesn't have a thermostat but it does have a timer that can be set to either off or on at a specific time, so i'll run it for a few hours in the night and before I go to bed to make sure the temps don't get too low.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That's the opposite of what you want.&amp;nbsp; A day/night temperature differential is beneficial.&amp;nbsp; Run the heater during the day to warm up the air around the terrarium, and don't worry about it dropping at night.&amp;nbsp; Place the terrarium near a bright window during the day to get some solar heating and you may not even need the heater.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd skip the idea of a hot rag under it.&amp;nbsp; The &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;shotgun terrarium&lt;/a&gt; works by having cooler air under and warmer air in the terrarium itself, caused by the lights and cakes or other substrates which provide heat.&amp;nbsp; Since warm air is less dense than cool air, the cool air from below comes up into the terrarium, scrubbing moisture from the perlite to humidify the air above.&amp;nbsp; Placing a heat source under the terrarium defeats the purpose.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16384199</next>\n<prev>16384084</prev>\n<first>16383937</first>\n<last>16389452</last>\n<when>1339761076</when>\n<utime>06/15/12 02:51 PM</utime>\n</post>"}